{"title_page": "List of tallest buildings in Singapore", "text_new": "{{Use Singapore English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n[[File:Singapore Skyline 2018.jpg|alt=The skyline of Singapore, showing its skyscrapers behind the Marina Bay.|thumb|300x300px|The skyline of Singapore in 2018. New buildings can be found on the left, which make up the [[Marina Bay Financial Centre]].]]\n[[File:Singapore Marina-Bay-Panorama-02.jpg|alt=Singapore skyline near a body of water, known as the Marina Bay.|thumb|300x300px|The skyline of Singapore in 2015]]\nThe [[city-state]] of [[Singapore]] has over 8,600<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/statistics/skyline-ranking|title=Skyline Ranking {{!}} Statistics {{!}} EMPORIS|website=www.emporis.com|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref> completed [[Tower block|high-rises]], the majority of it being located in the [[Downtown Core]], the city centre of Singapore. <ref name=\"EMPHR\">{{cite web | publisher = Emporis.com | title = Tall Buildings of Singapore | url = http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/ci/bu/sk/?id=100422 | accessdate = 18 July 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070204162539/http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/ci/bu/sk/?id=100422 | archivedate = 4 February 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In the city, there are about 80 skyscrapers. [[Guoco Tower]] currently holds the title of tallest building in Singapore. It stands at 290m (951 ft), exempted from the [[height restriction laws|height restriction]] of 280m in the [[Downtown Core, Singapore|Central Business District]].\n\nSingapore's history of skyscrapers began with the 1939 completion of the 17-storey [[Cathay Building]].<ref name=\"CATHAY emp\">{{cite web|publisher=Emporis.com|title=Cathay Building|url=http://www.emporis.com/application/?nav=building&lng=3&id=166657|accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref> The {{convert|70|m|ft|adj=on|0}} structure was, at the time of its completion, the tallest building in Southeast Asia; it was superseded by the {{convert|87|m|ft|adj=on|0}} [[Asia Insurance Building]] in 1954, which remained the tallest in Singapore until the {{convert|100|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=on|0}} [[Shaw House and Centre|Shaw Centre]] was completed in 1958.<ref name=\"AIB\"/><ref name=\"SHAW sky\">{{cite web|url=http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=24193|title=Shaw Centre|accessdate=14 July 2009|publisher=SkyscraperPage.com}}</ref> Singapore went through a major building boom in the 1970s and 1980s that resulted from the city's rapid industrialisation. During this time, the Overseas Union Bank Centre became the tallest building in the city-state; the {{convert|280|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=on|0}} structure was also the tallest building in the world outside of North America from its 1986 completion until 1989, when the [[Bank of China Tower, Hong Kong|Bank of China Tower]] in [[Hong Kong]] was completed.<ref name=\"OUB emp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=oubcentre-singapore-singapore|title=OUB Centre|publisher=Emporis.com|accessdate=16 July 2009}}</ref> The skyscraper-building boom continued during the 1990s and 2000s, with 30&nbsp;skyscrapers at least {{convert|140|m|ft|abbr=on|0}} tall, many of them residential towers, constructed from 1990 through 2008.\n\nSince 2000, there has been a sharp increase in the number of skyscrapers under construction in the city area, particularly in the [[Marina Bay, Singapore|Marina Bay]] district. One project completed in [[Marina Centre]] is the [[Marina Bay Financial Centre]], which includes 3 office towers offering {{convert|3000000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of prime Grade A office space, 2 residential developments offering 649 luxurious apartments and a {{convert|176000|sqft|m2|order=flip|adj=on}} retail mall, named Marina Bay Link Mall.<ref name=\"MarBR sky\">{{cite web|url=http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=56225|title=Marina Bay Residences|accessdate=15 July 2009|publisher=SkyscraperPage.com}}</ref> There are also several new developments in the city's shopping hub, [[Orchard Road]]. [[ION Orchard and The Orchard Residences|The Orchard Residences]] is a completed {{convert|218|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=on|0}}, 52-floor tower being built in conjunction with [[ION Orchard and The Orchard Residences|ION Orchard]], a shopping centre just beside [[Orchard MRT station]].<ref name=\"ION emp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/application/?nav=building&id=244944|title=The Orchard Residences|publisher=Emporis.com|accessdate=13 July 2009}}</ref> In addition, the {{convert|245|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=on|0}} [[Ocean Financial Centre]], a 43-floor skyscraper, is built in [[Raffles Place]].<ref name=\"OFC1 sky\">{{cite web|url=http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=69719|title=Ocean Financial Centre|publisher=SkyscraperPage.com|accessdate=16 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n__TOC__\n\n{{wide image|Singapore Panorama v2.jpg|900px|align-cap=center|Panorama of Singapore's skyline at dusk|alt=Skyline of a city, showing several tall skyscrapers. The tallest buildings are at the left and right of the image, with several low-rises in the immediate foreground. Most of the towers are lit up, as night is approaching}}\n\n==Tallest buildings==\nThis lists ranks Singapore skyscrapers that stand at least {{convert|140|m|ft|abbr=on|0}} tall, based on standard height measurement. This includes spires and architectural details but does not include antenna masts. An equal sign (=) following a rank indicates the same height between two or more buildings. The \"Year\" column indicates the year in which a building was completed.\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Name\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n! Height (m)\n! Height (ft)\n! Floors\n! Year\n! Coordinates\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1\n|[[Guoco Tower]]\n|[[File:Tanjong Pagar Centre.jpg|80px]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 290\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 951\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 64\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2016\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{coord|1|16|37.560|N|103|50|45.960|E}}\n|The tallest building in Singapore.<ref name=tanjongpagar/> Permission needed to be obtained, which was granted, to build it at 290m as there is a height limit of 280m allowable for buildings in Singapore.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/tanjong-pagar-centre-set-to-be-tallest-building-at-290m |title=Tanjong Pagar Centre set to be tallest building at 290m |date=3 May 2013 |author=Melissa Tan |work=The Straits Times }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2=\n| <span style=\"display:none\">29.0</span>[[One Raffles Place|One Raffles Place Tower 1]]\n|[[File:OUB Centre.JPG|80px|alt=Ground-level view of 60-storey building whose cross section is a square with a diagonal projection from one corner. In the top 10 storeys part of the square is missing and only a diagonal remains.]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 280\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 920\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 63\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1986\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{coord|1|17|04.89|N|103|51|03.70|E}}\n| Tied with [[Republic Plaza, Singapore|Republic Plaza]] and [[UOB Plaza|United Overseas Bank Plaza One]] as the tallest building in Singapore and the [[List of tallest buildings in the world|123rd-tallest in the world]]; stood as the tallest building outside North America from 1986 until the 1989 completion of the [[Bank of China Tower, Hong Kong|Bank of China Tower]] in Hong Kong; tallest building constructed in Singapore in the 1980s<ref name=\"OUB emp\" />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2=\n| <span style=\"display:none\">36.0</span>[[Republic Plaza, Singapore|Republic Plaza]]\n|[[File:Republic Plaza.jpg|80px|alt=Ground-level view of 70-storey building. The exterior has a reddish hue with dark windows. The building tapers slightly at two points.]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 280\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 920\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 66\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{coord|1|16|58|N|103|51|04|E}}\n| Tied with [[UOB Plaza|United Overseas Bank Plaza One]] and [[One Raffles Place| One Raffles Place Tower 1]] in Singapore and the 123rd-tallest in the world; tied as the tallest building constructed in Singapore in the 1990s<ref name=\"RP emp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=republicplaza-singapore-singapore|title=Republic Plaza|publisher=Emporis.com|accessdate=16 July 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"RP sky\">{{cite web | publisher = SkyscraperPage.com | title = Republic Plaza | url = http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=136 | accessdate = 31 January 2008 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2=\n| [[UOB Plaza|United Overseas Bank Plaza One]]\n|[[File:UOBnOUB.JPG|80px|alt=Ground-level view of several skyscrapers; the building on the right is the tallest and has a square cross section with several diagonal protrusions. A shorter building on the left resembles it closely.]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 280\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 920\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 67\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1992\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{coord|1|17|08|N|103|50|59|E}}\n| Tied with [[One Raffles Place| One Raffles Place Tower 1]] and [[Republic Plaza, Singapore|Republic Plaza]] as the tallest building in Singapore and the 123rd-tallest in the world; tied as the tallest building constructed in Singapore in the 1990s<ref name=\"UOB emp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=uobplaza1-singapore-singapore|title=UOB Plaza One|publisher=Emporis.com|accessdate=16 July 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"UOBP1 sky\">{{cite web | publisher = SkyscraperPage.com | title = United Overseas Bank Plaza One | url = http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=1615 | accessdate = 30 January 2008 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |5\n| <span style=\"display:none\">05.0</span>[[Capital Tower, Singapore|Capital Tower]]\n|[[File:Capital Tower, Jan 06.JPG|80px|alt=Ground-level view of a 50-storey building with a rectangular cross section; near the 40th floor the building tapers inward]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 254\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 833\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 52\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2000\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{coord|1|16|39|N|103|50|51|E}}\n| [[List of tallest buildings in the world|182nd-tallest building in the world]]; tallest building constructed in Singapore in the 2000s<ref>{{cite web | publisher = Emporis.com | title = Capital Tower | url = http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=capitaltower-singapore-singapore | accessdate = 24 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | publisher = SkyscraperPage.com | title = Capital Tower | url = http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=628 | accessdate = 31 January 2008 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |6=\n| <span style=\"display:none\">05.0</span>[[Altez]]\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 250\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 820\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 62\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{coord|1|16|28.2|N|103|50|39.5|E}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fareast.com.sg/FEOCorp.Web/index.aspx?page=home-prop-info&prop=211 |title=Altez \u2013 Far East Organization |publisher=Fareast.com.sg |accessdate=5 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127143934/http://www.fareast.com.sg/FEOCorp.Web/index.aspx?page=home-prop-info&prop=211 |archivedate=27 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |6=\n| <span style=\"display:none\">05.0</span>[[Skysuites @ Anson]]\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 250\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 820\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 72\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{coord|1|16|28.2|N|103|50|41.1|E}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wohhup.com/our-projects/skysuites-anson |title=Woh Hup (